## 🔄 Syncing Your Data (Push & Pull)

Your data (tasks, sleep, money, etc.) normally only lives in the browser you're using.
To carry it between devices — like your phone and laptop — use the **Sync tab**
inside the app.

### One-time setup
1. Go to https://github.com and create a free account (if you don't have one).
2. Click your profile picture (top right) → **Settings**.
3. Scroll down the left sidebar → **Developer settings**.
4. Click **Personal access tokens** → **Tokens (classic)**.
5. Click **Generate new token** → **Generate new token (classic)**.
6. Give it any name (e.g. `chaos-os`).
7. Under scopes, check only the box labeled **gist**. Leave everything else unchecked.
8. Click **Generate token** at the bottom.
9. Copy the token shown (starts with `ghp_...`) — you can only see it once, so copy
   it now.
10. In the app, go to the **Sync** tab, paste the token into "GitHub Token", click
    **Save**.

### Pushing (saving your data to the cloud)
1. Go to the **Sync** tab.
2. Click **↑ PUSH**.
3. That's it — your data is now saved. The first time you do this, a "Gist ID" will
   auto-fill on screen. Save that ID somewhere too (note app, screenshot, etc.) —
   you'll need it on your other device.

### Pulling (loading your data on another device)
1. On the new device, open the app and go to the **Sync** tab.
2. Paste in the **same** GitHub token you used before, click **Save**.
3. Paste in the **Gist ID** from the push step, click **Set**.
4. Click **↓ PULL**.
5. Your data from the other device now appears here.

**Heads up:** Pushing always overwrites your saved backup completely. If you make
changes on two devices before syncing, whichever one you push *last* wins, and the
other device's changes get overwritten.

## 📅 Syncing with Google Calendar

This lets you push events from the app's Calendar tab into your real Google
Calendar, and pull your Google Calendar events back into the app. It needs a
one-time setup since Google requires every app to register itself first.

### One-time setup

1. Go to https://console.cloud.google.com and sign in with your Google account.
2. Click the project dropdown at the top → **New Project**.
3. Name it anything (e.g. `chaos-os`) → **Create**. Wait a few seconds, then make
   sure it's selected in the dropdown.
4. In the search bar at the top, type **Google Calendar API**, click it, then click
   **Enable**.
5. In the left sidebar, click **APIs & Services** → **OAuth consent screen**.
   - User type: **External** → **Create**.
   - Fill in the app name (anything) and your email in the two required fields →
     keep clicking through the steps, leaving everything else default, until it's
     created.
6. Still on that consent screen, scroll to **Test users** → **+ Add users** → type
   in your own Gmail address → **Save**. (This step is required — without it,
   Google will block your own sign-in.)
7. In the left sidebar, click **Credentials** → **Create Credentials** → **OAuth
   client ID**.
   - Application type: **Web application**.
   - Under "Authorized JavaScript origins," click **+ Add URI** and enter your
     site's address with nothing after the domain — no path, no trailing slash.
     Example: `https://yourusername.github.io` (NOT
     `https://yourusername.github.io/your-repo/`).
   - Click **Create**.
8. Copy the **Client ID** shown (ends in `.apps.googleusercontent.com`).
9. In the app, go to the **Calendar** tab, paste it into "OAUTH CLIENT ID" → **Save**.

### Connecting

1. In the Calendar tab, click **🔗 Connect**.
2. A Google sign-in popup appears — pick your account, approve access.
3. The status line should show "✓ Connected to Google Calendar."

### Pushing events (app → Google Calendar)

Click any day on the calendar grid, add an event, then click **↑ Push Events**.
Only new events get sent — anything already pushed won't duplicate.

### Pulling events (Google Calendar → app)

Click **↓ Pull Events**. This brings in anything on your real Google Calendar from
roughly the past month through the next six months, and adds it to the app's
calendar (marked with a small "G" tag so you can tell it came from Google).

**Heads up:** You'll need to reconnect (click Connect again) each time you open a
new browser session — the connection isn't saved permanently for security reasons,
only your Client ID is remembered.

**You can use my pre-made web client : 960256795586-mbh30v8gla1tr7vq25ujq5q6m6e538nr.apps.googleusercontent.com**
